Utah CFP Oregon CHL Concealed Carry Class

Friday, August 22, 2014 7:00 PM

Silver Dragon Martial Arts, 7881 SW Cirrus Dr Bldg 25D, Beaverton, OR 97008

Class cost is $65. Save $5 by pre-registering online!

This class covers everything you need to get your Oregon Concealed Handgun License and your Utah Concealed Firearms Permit. 

Our course exceeds all firearms safety training exceeds the requirements to obtain your Utah CFP, pursuant to Utah Code Title 53 Chapter 5 Section 704, and your Oregon CHL pursuant to ORS 166.291(f)(G). 

Our process starts with issuing you a packet of information, an application for your permit, and fingerprint cards that you will need. We will do your fingerprinting, take your passport photo and make copies of your driver's license before class starts. We do this so that upon completion of this class, you will have a complete packet which you can submit to Utah BCI (Bureau of Criminal Identification) with your payment. You will also have all the information you need to obtain your Oregon CHL from your local Sheriff's department. 

Subjects covered are: Basic Handgun Safety, Tactical Issues, Concealed Carry Firearm selection tips, Ammunition, Holsters, Gun Free Zones, Reciprocity, Cleaning, Storage, Firearm Transport, Justifiable Force, Criminal and Civil liability, How to interact with Law Enforcement, and how to apply for your Permit. 

After attending this class you will have a fundamental understanding about handgun safety and the rights and responsibilities and laws associated with the carrying of a concealed Handgun in multiple states. 

This is NOT a live firing class. Do NOT bring a firearm with you to the class. 

Even though the class time is only scheduled to be 2 1/2 hours long, there will be time for questions and answers after the class. 

More Information: http://www.keepcalmandcarry.net/utah-cfp-oregon-chl-concealed-carry-class-22-8-2014-Schedule

title: For Sale:  Pact Scale/Dispenser
postcontent:
For sale, one PACT Scale and powder dispenser. Working with our Digital Precision Powder Scale the High Speed Dispenser will automatically give you the exact charge weight you've asked for. Want 61.9 grains? Type it in and press Dispense. Your Dispenser will take it from there, depositing your powder directly into the powder pan resting on the Scale. The Scale tells the Dispenser the actual charge weight as it's being dispensed using our infrared data port. The information from the Scale allows the dispenser to precisely meter the charges, trickling the last few tenths. In other words, each load is as accurate as it would be if you weighed each charge, trickling each one to the correct weight by hand. Scale can be used alone.

Used but in fully working order. Comes with scale, dispenser, 2 calibration weights, pan, 2 AC power adapters.

title: For Sale:  1980's Coly Python
postcontent:
Hooooooly craaaaap! Say what? A Python? For reals? No way! Yes way! 
Image

Stuff came up. Said stuff requires me to have money. So I'm sellin' the Python. Serial dates it to the 80's. And yep. It's a shooter. This isn't your "ultra rare stuck in a box in an attic for 40 years" python. This is a "Holy crap I'mma buy this and all my friends will be way jelly at the range" python. 

Mechanically this thing is sound. Tight. How tight? Tight. Tight like a tiger. The lockup is that tight. It has some light wear at the muzzle, and a small ding on the left side on the top strap behind the front sight. There's another small ding on the sight itself. So it's kinda a sleeper. It looks deadly mint until you get close up and notice the small imperfections that give this thing character. Yeah. I said it. Character. Use. Honest wear. A shooter that isn't some gunshow "Oh Yeah this is my grandfathers carry gun from aught 9 when he was chaisin' the Kaiser"
 story. 

The sights? They adjust. That's what they do. They're very flexible. They can go up or down. That's options right there. The grips are in fantastic shape. Basically, you should buy this gun and be all giddy with glee. That's all I'm sayin'. 

And you can buy it, for 1,600$. Cash money. No other forms of currency accepted. FTF, and I can meet half way maybe depending on distance, what my mood is and if I like you. CHL shown at the time of purchase to prove residency. Why not just a simple DL? I dunno. Just to be silly. The dings are shown in the pictures below. As far as trades? Meh. Wow me. Maybe we could work something out, but don't hold your breath. Even if I really like it I'll probably seem disinterested to bring the price on it's trade value lower.

title: For Sale:  Howa 1500 Supreme Varminter Sub MOA .308 WIN Bolt Action 24" Heavy Barrel
postcontent:
This rifle was built for me by a former Army Sniper and founder of Sniper Central. It shoots between .5 to .75 MOA (that is 1/2" to 3/4" groups at 100 yards).  The rifle is built on a Howa 1500 heavy barreled action which is a push feed style bolt action. There is a sako style extractor as well as a three position safety. The barrel is a heavy contour with a muzzle diameter of .815". The bottom of the action is flat providing a solid mounting area and there is a hinged floorplate with an internal magazine that holds 5 rounds. The metal finish is a semi-matte black color.  

The stock is a Bell & Carlson Medalist stock with a full aluminum bedding block. The barrels are free floated all the way to the action. The B&C Mk2 style stock is a tactical style stock that has a flat forend and a vertical pistol grip. The pistol grip is fairly large and fills the hand nicely.

It has a Harris Bipod.

The glass is a SWFA SS 10x42.  (+$240 if you want the glass).  http://swfa.com/SWFA-SS-10x42-Tactical-30mm-Riflescope-P499.aspx

Nothing wrong with the rifle at all.  It is fun to shoot.  I bought it with the idea to carry it in my Law Enforcement job, but our Department changed policy to only carrying AR type rifles, so I need to build an AR-10.

I will take trade for AR-10 type rifles.

title: For Sale:  SPRINGFIELD MODEL 1873 TRAPDOOR .45-70 GOV'T
location: Coastal Cash Exchange, 7718 Market St, Wilmington, North Carolina
postcontent:
This is a vintage Springfield Model 1873 "Trapdoor" breech-loading rifle chambered for .45-70 Government. In 1873 a U.S. Military boat conducted an examination and trial of 99 rifles from several domestic and foreign manufacturers, including submissions from Springfield, Remington, Winchester, and Sharps in the search for a breech loading rifle and carbine. The keltec plastic hand guards were removed and the red lion precision rotating guard was installed. Two red lion rails were purchased, one for top and one for bottom. Red lion muzzle compensator was installed and I have one backup. TandemKross hex screw upgrade set was installed on all rifle screws. Rubber magpul guards were installed around red lion part for aesthetic and grip. A folding foregrip is included and has a bipod attachment. Also pictured is a butt stock universal addon cushion.
